  "doc_id": "40100",
  "text": "Essential oils had a clear dose-dependent antifungal activity on A. flavus at the concentration tested in our agar dilution assay to determine MICs. Our finding suggests that the increment of dose to 2, 4, and 8 L/mL have a significant effect on the inhibition of fungal in reduction of fungal growth while all tested doses have significant effect in inhibition of spore germination. Absolute inhibition of fungal growth were seen at a concentration of 2 L/mL, 4 L/mL, and 8 L/mL for the essential oils of T. ammi, C. martinii, and F. vulgare, respectively, and the concentrations were recorded as MICs. Volatile constituents of the essential oils, might create vapor action which could be responsible for the activities [CITATION_1] . Previous study reported antifungal property of essential oils, certainly, differences in major and minor constituents of the oils that are responsible for their biological activity by geographical location and seasons of collection and the difference in test organisms used in the study could contribute to the difference in MIC of C. martinii [CITATION_2] , F. vulgare [CITATION_3] , and T. ammi [CITATION_4] .",
